Mom, I'm going to the gym tonight, so don't wait for me for dinner. The report went quite smoothly today; we can talk more when I get back tonight.

Mom, I had a light lunch with colleagues outside at noon, and I bought you some walnut shortbread and mung bean cakes from Jinweizhai. I'll bring them back tonight. Merry Christmas Eve!

Dad, I'll be home around 1:40 p.m. this afternoon. I've brought the hand gripper you tried last time—I've made some improvements to it, so it should feel much better now. Please help me test it out again.

Mr. Zhou, Mr. Li, I thoroughly enjoyed our conversation at noon today, and the collaboration concept holds great promise. I have drafted a preliminary functional framework and will bring it to the office next Monday for us to refine together.
Mom, I'm home. I had dumplings for dinner. You and Dad should rest early tonight.
Kai, logging in after 10 p.m.? Feeling good today, aiming to climb the ranks.

Dr. Liu, hello. This is Ye Mingxuan, who had the physical examination this morning. Regarding the cervical spine health exercises and diaphragmatic breathing techniques you mentioned, I would like to confirm the frequency and duration of practice. Is it twice a day, morning and evening, for 10 minutes each time? Coach Wang, I'll arrive at the gym in about 15 minutes. Today, I'd like to focus on core training and stretching. If it's convenient for you, could you please check my form? Thank you.

Coach Wang, hello. I have just completed my physical examination, and the doctor advised paying attention to neck and shoulder protection as well as core training during exercise, with the elliptical machine being the primary choice for aerobic activities. I would like to discuss with you to see if it is possible to adjust my subsequent training plan based on these recommendations.
Mom, I've bought the groceries. I'll cook dinner tonight—steamed fish and garlic-flavored Chinese flat cabbage, with brown rice as the staple. About what time will you be home?
Mom, I slept fairly well last night, though my neck is still a bit stiff. How about you? The millet porridge for breakfast was really delicious—thank you.

message_content: Wang Jian: Mingxuan, tonight is the first resistance training session at Waterside Garden Gym. Remember to do barbell squats, barbell bench press, seated cable rows, leg press, and finish with core training.
Ye Mingxuan: The training session has ended. For the core workout, I didn't do pull-ups; instead, I did planks and Russian twists. It felt good.
Shall we do something meaningful together tonight? The one we discussed during lunch.
Father: Son, the medical check-up is at the University of Traditional Chinese Medicine tomorrow. Don't forget to fast.
Ye Mingxuan: The vehicle has been repaired. It is located on an unnamed dirt road about 3 kilometers from the main road on the West Ring Road of Gangcha County. We are returning immediately.
Zhao Xiaofeng: Mingxuan, how has your lower back been recovering lately? Does it still hurt?
Ye Mingxuan: Much better, thank you, Xiaofeng. I can get out of bed and move around now, but I still can't sit for too long. How about you? Have you been busy lately?

Zhao Xiaofeng: Don't even mention it. We're also racing against the clock on the suspension system design for a new vehicle model here. By the way, I had a video call with Liu Yang yesterday, and he's having an even tougher time over there.
Ye Mingxuan: What's wrong with Yangzi? Is the project in Shenzhen not going smoothly?

Zhao Xiaofeng: Yeah, he's in charge of a smart home gateway project. The hardware plan was already finalized, but then the client, for some inexplicable reason, suddenly demanded to switch the main control chip from STM32 to NXP's i.MX RT series. Now, all the underlying drivers have to be rewritten, and the application layer needs modifications as well. The entire project team is working overtime, and a delay is absolutely inevitable. He complained to me, saying that such last-minute hardware changes are the most troublesome.
Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, a few new movies have been released recently. Would you like to go see them this weekend? It would be a good way to relax.
Ye Mingxuan: Sure, any recommendations? I've been cooped up at home lately and really need to get out for some fresh air.

Zhou Tao: There's a domestic sci-fi film called "Deep Space Era," which is said to have impressive special effects. There's also a Hollywood thriller titled "Deadly Code," which has received high ratings. Oh, and there's a romance film called "After Meeting You," starring that popular young actress and heartthrob who have been trending lately.

Ye Mingxuan: Sci-fi and suspense films are worth checking out. As for romance movies, well, you know—I really can't get into those overly sentimental ones that rely entirely on coincidences to drive the plot. They just don't seem logically convincing to me. I'd rather watch something with a bit of technical depth or that requires some brainpower.
Zhou Tao: Haha, I knew you'd say that. Alright, let's check the showtimes for "Deep Space Era" and "Fatal Code." The practical ISTJ brain refuses mindless romance.
Zhang Wei: Brother Xuan, how have you been lately? Is your back feeling any better?
Ye Mingxuan: Much better. Working from home and recovering gradually. How about you? What have you been up to lately?
Zhang Wei: Sigh, there's something going on at home. My uncle, my mother's own brother, was just diagnosed with diabetes, and it's quite serious.
Ye Mingxuan: Huh? So sudden. Hasn't your uncle's health always been fairly good?

Zhang Wei: Exactly. Usually it seems fine, but when tested, the blood sugar level is alarmingly high. The doctor said it's due to long-term poor dietary habits and lack of exercise. It served as a wake-up call for me too. I've decided to quit soda and milk tea from now on, cut back on barbecue, and start exercising.
Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, have you watched the new season of "The Brain" recently? The mental arithmetic segment is absolutely incredible!
Ye Mingxuan: I've watched a few episodes. That mental arithmetic contestant is truly impressive, but it seems his performance fluctuates quite a bit. He made a mistake in the last episode.

Zhou Tao: Haha, that's exactly the kind of drama I'm looking for! I prefer watching those dark horses that make a stunning debut—it's so thrilling. What about you? What kind of contestants do you like?
Ye Mingxuan: It might be related to my work habits. I actually appreciate players who take every step steadily and consistently perform at 80–90% of their potential.

Ye Mingxuan: Just like in design, one-time brilliance is not as valuable as consistent reliability. Those who win with low error rates, relying on solid fundamentals and a steady mindset, are more convincing in my view.
Ye Mingxuan: Just got on the subway, it's a bit crowded. I'll listen to something on the way. Have you arrived at the company?
Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, please bring me a drink during the break. Meet at the usual place.
Just had a great find at the Gulou Antique Market—picked up a wonderful book!
Mom: The park's walking path seems well-maintained and feels stable to walk on. Perhaps we could bring Dad here for a walk—it would be good for his recovery.
Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, I think the plan we discussed during lunch today is excellent. Let's discuss it in more detail over the weekend.

Ye Mingxuan: Coach Wang, I just finished my follow-up appointment. Dr. Liu said my lumbar spine is recovering well, with basically normal range of motion. However, I still need to be careful and avoid lifting heavy objects for now.
Sun Jing: Mingxuan, have you been in touch with Liu Yang recently? He seems to be in a bit of a low mood.

Ye Mingxuan: We chatted briefly while gaming last week, and he did seem a bit worn out. He mentioned that their company had landed a major order, and the embedded module he’s responsible for needed to be delivered urgently. He had been working overtime for two consecutive weeks and was completely exhausted.

Sun Jing: No wonder. His girlfriend complained to me, saying that last week was their third anniversary of being together, but Liu Yang completely forgot about it. He worked overtime until midnight before coming home, and they had a big argument. They are still giving each other the cold shoulder now.

Ye Mingxuan: Sigh, the pace over in Shenzhen is indeed fast. Although our projects here are also tight, at least we have a flexible work system now, so we can take care of things at home. As for his situation, there's not much I can do to help. I can only wait for him to calm down a bit before trying to talk to him again.

Sun Jing: Indeed, every family has its own difficulties. Take good care of yourself, and while looking after your uncle, don't forget to pay attention to your own health. I'll organize a gathering later so that a few of us from Tianjin can get together.
Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, any good variety shows to recommend lately? Have you watched the new season of "Keep Running"? It feels like it's all scripted, not interesting at all.
Ye Mingxuan: I stopped watching that a long time ago. Now I mainly watch shows like "The Brain" and "RoboMaster."
Zhou Tao: Oh? Why do you prefer this kind? It feels a bit mind-bending.

Ye Mingxuan: It's a professional habit. Watching contestants solve problems and design robot battles, that kind of step-by-step logical deduction and the hardcore technical implementation process are much more enjoyable than watching celebrities play games. You can learn some ideas from it.
Zhou Tao: Got it. Your ISTJ taste is indeed pragmatic. Then I'll give "RoboMaster" a try. I've heard the algorithms and mechanical design in it are quite professional.
Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, I just finished a video call with Yangzi (Liu Yang). This guy has been really busy lately.
Ye Mingxuan: Oh? Is he rushing the project schedule again?
Zhou Tao: It's not about work. It's a major life event! He finally settled on a house in Shenzhen, near the Science and Technology Park in Nanshan District.
Ye Mingxuan: Wow, impressive! Shenzhen's housing prices are no joke. He's really putting down roots there.

Zhou Tao: Yeah, he's busy with the renovation right now, complaining to me every day about the hassle of selecting materials and supervising the construction site, saying it's even more exhausting than coding. But seeing how excited he is, all that effort is worth it.
Zhao Jianguo: Mingxuan, there's a batch of Beiyang 34th Year Dragon Dollars on the market recently with excellent condition. Have you been paying attention?

Ye Mingxuan: Hello, Teacher Zhao. I haven't looked into the Beiyang Dragon coin for the time being. My taste has changed a bit recently, and I've lost interest in those smooth "original luster coins."
Zhao Jianguo: Oh? So what type are you more interested in now?

Ye Mingxuan: I've recently become particularly fascinated with copper coins bearing stamps or ink annotations. For example, those stamped with verification marks from money shops or merchant houses, or those with handwritten notes in ink brush by old accountants.

Ye Mingxuan: I believe these traces tell a more compelling story than the coins themselves, revealing their "life trajectory" throughout circulation. Cleaning and studying these marks is like being a historical detective—it’s particularly fascinating.
Zhao Xiaofeng: Mingxuan, how have you been lately? I had a video call with Liu Yang last week, and it seems he's encountered some technical issues on his end.
Ye Mingxuan: I'm doing alright. What's wrong with Liu Yang? He works in embedded software, so his issues should be quite specific.

Zhao Xiaofeng: Yes, he is responsible for an in-vehicle controller project, which is currently undergoing low-temperature testing. He mentioned that the CAN bus communication occasionally experiences frame loss in environments around minus 20 degrees Celsius. The probability is not high, but it is quite troublesome, as both reproduction and localization of the issue are difficult.

Ye Mingxuan: This is indeed tricky; it could be either hardware or software. I work in mechanics and don't have a deep understanding of communication protocols, so I can't be of much help. Did he consult the hardware experts from his company to take a look together?

Zhao Xiaofeng: He said they are currently investigating with the hardware team, and it might be an issue with the low-temperature characteristics of a certain component or the PCB layout. Hopefully, he can resolve it soon.
Zhao Jianguo: Mingxuan, have you received any good items lately? I noticed there's another batch of dragon dollars coming up for auction in the catalog.

Ye Mingxuan: Hello, Professor Zhao. I've temporarily stopped collecting Longyang for now, as the prices have been driven too high and the cost-performance ratio is average. My interests have shifted a bit recently.
Zhao Jianguo: Oh? Which direction has it turned? Yuan Datou or Sun Xiaotou?

Ye Mingxuan: Neither. I've become particularly fascinated by the machine-struck copper coins that various provinces trial-minted in the late Qing Dynasty. For example, the "Guangxu Yuanbao" ten-cash copper coins have numerous provincial variations, significant differences in design details, and distinct historical transitional characteristics. Moreover, their current market prices have not yet fully appreciated, leaving room for exploration.

Zhao Jianguo: This is an excellent research direction! Mechanism copper coins truly serve as living fossils for studying China's modern monetary history and local finance. Particularly, trial minting versions and early circulation editions reveal much about the evolution of craftsmanship and design changes. I have some reference materials on hand and will share them with you later for your reference.
Sun Jing: Mingxuan, have you been busy lately? I just had a phone call with Liu Yang, and there's been a significant change on his end.
Ye Mingxuan: Hello, Sister Jing. I just got off work. What happened to Liu Yang? He mentioned his project was tight when we played games last week.

Sun Jing: He has resigned! He said he had given it a lot of thought and felt that although working in embedded development at Shenzhen Huachuang Microelectronics was stable, the career ceiling was clearly visible.
Ye Mingxuan: What? So sudden. What are his plans next? Returning to the north?

Sun Jing: No, he stayed in Shenzhen. He partnered with two technical friends he knew before and is planning to start his own business. The focus is on Industrial Internet of Things, or IIoT. He believes this field, which combines hardware and software, has great prospects. He even asked if we wanted to invest a small amount to support him, haha.
Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, did you watch the new season of "Go Fighting!" last night? The desert island survival segment was so thrilling that it made me want to go camping.
Ye Mingxuan: I watched the beginning. I usually fast-forward through those purely physical ones. I prefer watching shows like "The Amazing Craftsmen" or "Skills in Action."

Zhou Tao: Oh right, you're an ISTJ, so you enjoy watching people work meticulously, right? Like competitions where they machine a part on a lathe or make mortise and tenon furniture without using a single nail?

Ye Mingxuan: Haha, you saw right through me. Yes, especially in timed competitions, watching how the contestants plan their steps, handle unexpected problems, and ultimately create something precise or ingenious is particularly thrilling. It's much more interesting than pure running and jumping or just talking.
Zhou Tao: Understood. Engineer Ye is a technically-oriented viewer. I'll recommend good mechanical assembly competition shows to you next time. Shall we go for a meal?
Ye Mingxuan: Mom made those classic snacks again this morning, really missing the taste of home. Getting ready to head out now!
Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, the meeting minutes have been uploaded to the group file. The points raised by Senior Engineer Gao require key follow-up. Please review them.

Today I accompanied my parents for a walk in Shuixi Park. My father was particularly curious about the arch bridge and kept asking how it bears the load. I had to use my knowledge of mechanics to give him a simple explanation, which was quite interesting.

Dear Dr. Liu,  

This is Ye Mingxuan. Thank you for the detailed explanation this morning. Regarding the exercise recommendations, I would like to confirm my understanding: the brisk walking and cycling you mentioned are two options, and either can be included as part of the twice-weekly exercise routine, correct? Each session should last at least 30 minutes, with an intensity level that results in light sweating and an increased heart rate. I plan to start implementing this routine from this week.
Just finished today's volunteer activity, where I answered many neighbors' questions about kitchen waste disposal. It felt very meaningful.
Zhang Wei: Xuanzi, are you free tonight? Let's go grab some barbecue. I've been dealing with a lot at the shop lately and would like to chat with you.
Ye Mingxuan: Sure, let's meet at the usual place. I actually have a few questions about the car I wanted to ask you.
Zhang Wei: Sigh, I had a chat with a buddy at the store today and felt quite emotional. He's also in sales and has been doing it for five or six years.
Zhang Wei: He believes there is limited growth potential in selling new cars and wants to shift towards used car appraisal, considering it a promising field.
Ye Mingxuan: Transformation is a good thing. Appraisers require a considerable amount of professional knowledge, right?

Zhang Wei: That's exactly the problem. He inquired around and found out that a certified appraiser requires specialized qualifications and systematic training; it's not something that can be done based on experience alone. He's stuck at this point, feeling a bit lost and unsure whether to invest the time and money to take the exam.
Sun Jing: Mingxuan, what have you been up to lately? Are you still following that variety show "Extreme Manufacturing"?
Ye Mingxuan: I'm watching, Sister Jing. The quality this season is quite high. But I've noticed my tastes have changed a bit.
Sun Jing: Oh? How so? Weren't you the one who used to love watching those experts showcase their individual skills, completing a complex structure in just a few minutes?

Ye Mingxuan: Yes, but now I feel that kind of thing, while satisfying, is somewhat detached from reality. In the recent episodes, there was a team challenge that required designing, processing, and assembling a small-scale assembly line within a time limit.

Ye Mingxuan: I was completely engrossed. Some team members excelled at design, others had steady hands suitable for precision assembly, and some were adept at coordinating schedules. Although there were occasional frictions during the process, the moment we achieved seamless collaboration and completed the task, it felt far more impressive than any individual performance. It closely mirrored the project dynamics we encounter in our actual work.
Sun Jing: Haha, it seems work has given you a deeper understanding of the word "team"—from appreciating individual heroism to valuing teamwork.
Sun Jing: Mingxuan, have you been in touch with Liu Yang recently? He seems to be in low spirits lately.
Ye Mingxuan: We exchanged a few words while playing games last week, and I felt he didn't say much. What's up?
Sun Jing: I heard him mention that his family is pressuring him to get married. He's been on a few blind dates in Shenzhen, but none of them have worked out well.
Ye Mingxuan: Well... He's naturally a bit introverted. He's fine with technical work, but probably won't be very comfortable chatting with strangers.

Sun Jing: Indeed, he himself said that when he gets nervous, he doesn't know what to say. After several such experiences, he feels quite discouraged and under a lot of pressure. Let's try to talk to him and offer some guidance later.
Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, there's a new sci-fi film "Deep Space Era" releasing during the National Day holiday. The special effects are said to be mind-blowing. Want to go watch it together?
Ye Mingxuan: Sci-fi sounds great. I've always been quite interested in hardcore settings and visual spectacles. As long as it's not the kind that's all mushy and focused on romance.
Zhou Tao: Haha, I knew you weren't into romance films. The trailer for "Love Letter Through Time" looked quite touching—are you sure you don't want to consider it?

Ye Mingxuan: Forget it. I'd rather watch mind-bending suspense films or ones with historical weight like "The Battle at Lake Changjin." Purely focusing on romance tends to be too slow-paced; I easily lose focus.
Zhou Tao: Got it, understood. Then it's settled on "Deep Space Era," I'll buy the tickets. We'll plan for the suspense and historical war films next time.

【Anxin Insurance】Dear Mr. Ye Mingxuan, the "Anxin Long-term Medical Insurance" you purchased for Ye XX has been underwritten and is now in effect. The policy number is AB20251121007, and the electronic policy has been sent to your email. Thank you for your trust! Location of policy purchase: Near Haitai Building, No. 6 Meiyuan Road, Xiqing District, Tianjin.
Zhang Wei: Mingxuan, are you free this weekend? I have some good news and would like to share it with someone.
Ye Mingxuan: Weizi, what's the good news? I should be free this weekend.
Zhang Wei: It wasn't me, it was my university classmate Wang Lei. Do you remember him? The one who works in embedded systems.
Ye Mingxuan: I remember, you've mentioned him several times. What happened to him?

Zhang Wei: He recently made a successful career move! He transitioned from his previous company to a top-tier domestic chip design firm, where he now works on core driver development. I heard his salary increased by over 40%—truly impressive.
Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, a new sci-fi film has recently been released, and the reviews seem quite positive. Would you like to go see it together this weekend?
Ye Mingxuan: Science fiction movies are fine with me, as long as they aren't too far-fetched or detached from reality.
Zhou Tao: Haha, I knew you'd prefer this more technical style. What about suspense films? My girlfriend has recently become obsessed with one and insists on dragging me to watch it.

Ye Mingxuan: Suspense films are also acceptable; it's quite interesting to engage the mind along with the plot. What I dread most are those slow-paced artistic romance films—they make me doze off, and I just can't grasp their appeal.
Zhou Tao: Understood. The taste of a pragmatic engineer. What about absurdist comedies? The kind purely for relaxation.
Ye Mingxuan: It's fine to watch that occasionally as background noise, no need to take it too seriously. But what really doesn't suit my taste are romantic art films—the pacing is just too slow.
Sun Jing: Mingxuan, have you been in touch with Liu Yang recently? He was complaining to me the other day, and it was both annoying and amusing.
Ye Mingxuan: Not yet, I've been busy with projects lately. What's wrong with him? Did he have another unusual encounter?
Sun Jing: Exactly. The apartment he rented in Shenzhen had an issue where the upstairs neighbor was renovating and somehow managed to burst a water pipe.

Sun Jing: Water was gushing down, soaking the ceiling of his home. The worst part was that the brand-new gaming console he had just splurged on was placed right underneath, and it got completely drenched.
Ye Mingxuan: ...That's just tragic. A brand new machine! He must be heartbroken.

Sun Jing: Indeed, he said he was getting a headache from arguing with the neighbors and the property management. But looking at that scrapped mainframe, he felt the whole situation was so absurd that he couldn't help but laugh in frustration—it was a mix of amusement and exasperation.
Zhao Jianguo: Mingxuan, there's a batch of goods on the market recently with excellent condition and almost no signs of circulation. Would you like to take a look at the pictures?
Ye Mingxuan: Thank you, Professor Zhao. However, my taste has changed a bit recently. Those overly new "original luster" coins, which are shiny and bright, always seem to lack a certain depth to me.
Zhao Jianguo: Oh? So what do you value more now?

Ye Mingxuan: I prefer coins with slight signs of use on their surfaces—not severe wear, but the kind that has been naturally aged over time, with a smooth and mellow patina that exudes a sense of "vintage charm." It feels as though every mark tells a story.

Zhao Jianguo: Haha, understood. The transition from pursuing "perfection" to appreciating "charm" is a common path for collectors to elevate their taste. I do have a few pieces on hand that match your description. I'll send them to you later for a look.
Ye Mingxuan: Currently at the building materials market, the shop owner is very enthusiastic and is explaining the characteristics and applicable scenarios of different types of wood.
Ye Mingyuan: Mingxuan, how have you been lately? Is it cold in Tianjin? It's damp and chilly here in Shenzhen, which is also quite uncomfortable.
Ye Mingxuan: Not bad, the heating is on at home. How's work going for you?
Ye Mingyuan: Same as usual, writing code. But I have a friend who works as a game planner. He just changed jobs, and it caused quite a stir.
Ye Mingxuan: Oh? From which point to which point has it jumped? The gaming industry is highly competitive now.

Ye Mingyuan: He went directly from an unknown small company to Tencent's TiMi Studio, becoming one of the lead designers for a new project. All of us friends are happy for him—it’s like a carp leaping over the dragon gate.
Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, did you watch the latest episode of "Extreme Manufacturing" last night? The challenge of building a catapult using wood and simple machinery was so cool!

Ye Mingxuan: I did. That team did well in their preliminary calculations, taking into account factors like the parabola, counterweight, and structural strength. Although the final accuracy was slightly off, their approach was very engineering-oriented.
Zhou Tao: Haha, I just love watching them scramble and ultimately fail—it's so dramatic. You seem to particularly enjoy these kinds of segments that require a lot of calculation, don't you?

Ye Mingxuan: Yes, I think what fascinates me most about this type of show is the engineering challenges. Watching how they turn theory into reality, how the team divides tasks, and how they solve unexpected problems is far more interesting than simply competing based on physical strength or luck. It's probably just a professional habit.
Zhou Tao: Understood, the romance of an ISTJ. I'll call you for this kind of activity next time. Shall we go eat?
Zhao Jianguo: Mingxuan, how have you been lately? I've encountered a minor academic issue and would like to discuss it with you.
Ye Mingxuan: Hello, Professor Zhao! I'm doing well. What's the trouble you mentioned? Is it related to ancient coin identification?

Zhao Jianguo: Yes. I am writing a thesis on the analysis of the varieties of the 'Jiangnan Province Made' silver coins from the late Qing Dynasty, and I need to refer to a sample coin of the Wuxu Jiangnan Dragon Silver Dollar held by the Tianjin Museum.
Ye Mingxuan: I know this coin. It is in excellent condition and is crucial for studying its varieties.

Zhao Jianguo: That's correct. However, the issue is that I contacted the museum, and neither their publicly available image library nor their internal archives contain high-resolution detail images of this coin, particularly close-ups of the edge reeding and dragon scales. Without these images, the arguments in my paper regarding several subtle varieties lack crucial supporting evidence, and I'm stuck at this point.

Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, I'm thinking of buying a Bluetooth speaker for the living room at home, to use for watching movies and listening to music on weekends. I see you usually have some knowledge about audio equipment, any recommendations? Or what do you value most when choosing a speaker?
Ye Mingxuan: I've been looking into it recently as well. For me, brand and smart features are secondary. What I value most are two key points.
Zhou Tao: Which two points? Please elaborate.

Ye Mingxuan: First is the depth and elasticity of the bass. It shouldn't just be booming; it needs to have texture. A lot of the music I listen to and movies I watch require this. Second is the openness of the soundstage and the sense of positioning. Ideally, it should create a certain sense of space rather than having all the sounds crammed together. Battery life and water resistance aren't essential for my home use scenario.
Zhou Tao: Understood. Your requirements are quite professional. It seems I should focus on models with good low-frequency drivers and acoustic structures. Thanks!
Liu Yang: Mingxuan, have you been busy lately? I've hit a bit of a bottleneck with my project, and it's a bit frustrating.
Ye Mingxuan: Not bad, just preparing for the self-driving trip to Qinghai Lake. What's going on with you? Is the Huachuang project not going smoothly?

Liu Yang: Well, frequent changes in client requirements have severely delayed the development progress of the core modules in the embedded software. The entire project may be postponed by a quarter. Several key engineers in the team have been working overtime excessively lately and are struggling to cope, leading to relatively low morale.

Ye Mingxuan: That does sound tricky. We occasionally encounter similar situations here as well, primarily relying on repeated communication with clients and internal resource adjustments. What's your project manager's stance on this?

Ye Mingxuan: By the way, I just had a meal with Xiaofeng, and we also talked about you. He mentioned that he recently heard about the high-pressure situation with some projects in Shenzhen and asked me to check if you need help connecting with some resources in Tianjin to relax a bit.

Manager Zhang: Hello, Mr. Ye. I am Zhang Wei from China Merchants Bank. The third-quarter market review and fourth-quarter outlook report have been sent to your email. I noticed that several of the hybrid funds you hold have performed steadily. Recently, our bank has been promoting several thematic funds focusing on new consumption scenarios. Would you be interested in learning more about them?
Ye Mingxuan: Hello, Manager Zhang. I have received the report. Thank you. Regarding funds focused on the consumer theme, I personally still maintain a relatively cautious stance at the moment.

Ye Mingxuan: I feel that after the price increases in recent years, the valuations of many consumer companies are no longer cheap, especially those promoting the so-called "new consumption" concept. After reviewing some research reports, I also believe that at the current level, the risk-reward ratio of the consumer sector may not be particularly ideal for someone like me who prioritizes stability. I still prefer the balanced allocation products or those with clear dividend strategies that you recommended earlier.

Manager Zhang: I understand your concerns, and I completely appreciate where you're coming from. Indeed, valuation is a key factor to consider in investment. Your approach has always been quite prudent. In that case, we will focus on tracking the performance of your current holdings and screening for alternative products with more reasonable valuations and a more diversified industry distribution. We will report back to you when suitable options arise.
Zhang Wei: Xuanzi, are you busy? I have something quite interesting to tell you.
Ye Mingxuan: Just got off work, what's up, Weizi?
Zhang Wei: My uncle was renovating the old house in our hometown in Cangzhou, and guess what? He dug up a jar of something right at the base of the wall.
Ye Mingxuan: Wow! Antiques?

Zhang Wei: Exactly! A whole jar of silver dollars, wrapped in several layers of oil paper. It looks like it's from the Republic of China era. My uncle was completely stunned and is having it appraised right now. Don't you know about these things? I'll take some photos and send them to you later.
Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, are you free this weekend? Li Xiang mentioned wanting to get together for a meal.
Ye Mingxuan: I'm free. What would you like to eat? I've been feeling like my food has been a bit bland lately.
Zhou Tao: Li Xiang suggested going to the newly opened Huaiyang cuisine restaurant, saying it's light and good for health.

Ye Mingxuan: Huaiyang cuisine... it's too mild. I've been craving something with strong flavors lately, something numbing and spicy, that really hits the spot. How about Sichuan or Hunan cuisine instead?
Zhou Tao: Haha, I knew you'd like that. Alright, I'll tell Li Xiang we're switching to a Sichuan restaurant. How about "Shuxiangge" behind the company?

Manager Wang, hello! Based on today's performance review, I have compiled the action items and plan to contact you tomorrow to discuss career development suggestions in detail. I look forward to your guidance.
Zhang Wei: Mingxuan, what have you been up to lately? Are you free to grab some skewers this weekend?
Ye Mingxuan: Sounds good, the weekend works. The project just wrapped up recently, so it's a good time to relax. Anything new on your end?

Zhang Wei: Oh, don't even get me started. There have been so many happy occasions in my family lately. My cousin, the one who's always been a top student since childhood, got accepted into graduate school this year!
Ye Mingxuan: Sure! Which school did you get into?
Zhang Wei: Tianjin University! Majoring in Mechanical Engineering, we're actually in the same field. My family is overjoyed and planning to host a few tables to celebrate.
Sun Jing: Mingxuan, have you been busy lately? I saw the woodworking project you posted on your Moments—your craftsmanship has really improved!
Ye Mingxuan: Not bad, same as usual. Woodworking is just a way to tinker around and relieve stress. How have you been doing in Beijing lately?
Sun Jing: Projects keep coming one after another, exhausting but fulfilling. Besides doing woodwork, what do you usually watch to relax? I remember you enjoy watching competitive reality shows.
Ye Mingxuan: Yes, I've been following the new season of "The Brain" recently. That kind of mind-bending competitive atmosphere really appeals to me—it's more interesting than pure entertainment.
Sun Jing: Really? I watch it occasionally too. Who do you like in it? I feel like all those contestants are incredibly amazing.

Ye Mingxuan: The contestants are indeed impressive, but I prefer the host Jiang Changjian. His composed, rational style, coupled with his precise commentary and ability to control the stage, is truly captivating. He feels like the epitome of an ISTJ, haha.
Sun Jing: Mingxuan, how have you been lately? It's been a while since there was any activity in our university classmates' group chat.
Ye Mingxuan: Hello, Sister Jing. I'm doing alright, just finished up with a project. It has been a while since I last spoke in the group chat. How have Liu Yang and Xiaofeng been lately?
Sun Jing: Xiaofeng is still the same as before, working diligently at FAW Tianjin. As for Liu Yang, he's been feeling a bit down lately.
Ye Mingxuan: Oh? What happened to him? Work-related issues?

Sun Jing: It's not about work, it's a personal issue. His family arranged a blind date for him, but the other person heard he works in embedded software and thought this field is unstable, with less promising prospects compared to big internet companies. They subtly looked down on him, which really upset Yangzi. He vented to me for a long time.
Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, any plans for the weekend? Want to go see the new Transformers movie together?

Ye Mingxuan: I'm afraid this weekend won't work. I need to go to the hardware market. The old screwdriver I have doesn't have enough torque—it was a struggle to disassemble the mortise and tenon joints of an old piece of furniture. I'm thinking of switching to an electric one.
Zhou Tao: Electric ones are great, they save effort. What do you mainly look for when choosing? Battery life?

Ye Mingxuan: Battery life is the foundation; it just needs to last me half a day. What I value most is that the maximum torque must be sufficient; otherwise, it's useless when dealing with hard wood or rusty screws. Additionally, having more gear options is important to handle both delicate tasks and heavy-duty work.
Zhou Tao: Understood. Brute force with finesse. That's quite an engineer's requirement. Let me know the model you decide on, I'll use it as a reference too.

Zhang Wei: Mingxuan, what have you been up to lately? That Brother Li from our shop, the one who knows a lot about the in-vehicle infotainment system we talked about last time, has been sent by the company to the Shanghai headquarters for training. He’ll be gone for three whole months.
Ye Mingxuan: Really? That's quite good. What kind of training are you going to attend?

Zhang Wei: The sales elite training seems to be organized by the headquarters, targeting key personnel from each store. With his departure, our team is under a bit more pressure, as many long-term clients specifically recognize him.

Ye Mingxuan: I understand. Losing key personnel is bound to have an impact. But it's good for his personal development. By the way, the test drive arrangement for that new car model you mentioned last time—has it been affected?
Zhang Wei: The test drive is no problem, I can arrange it on my end. It's just that I'm missing a companion to smoke and complain with, haha. How's your project going lately?
Sun Jing: Mingxuan, any good variety shows to recommend lately? I'm running out of dramas to watch.

Ye Mingxuan: I've been watching a lot of competitive shows lately. But my taste has changed a bit. I used to enjoy watching celebrities running and jumping around, but now I find that kind of thing boring.
Sun Jing: Oh? So what do you like to watch now? It wouldn't be "If You Are the One," would it? Haha.

Ye Mingxuan: That's impossible. Recently, I discovered a show called "Extreme Manufacturing," where engineers and technicians from various industries participate. They are given materials and a theme, and they compete to create something within a limited time. The rules are extremely detailed, and the judging is professional. It's incredibly engaging to watch—much more interesting than purely entertainment-focused shows.
Sun Jing: Sounds pretty hardcore, which fits your STEM guy vibe. Alright, I'll look it up and give my brain a break. Thanks!
Zhang Wei: Brother Xuan, what have you been up to lately? Something happened at our store recently, and it's got everyone on edge.
Ye Mingxuan: Just got off work, about to have dinner. What happened at your store? Is it related to a car?
Zhang Wei: Yes, a colleague of mine who I get along with quite well got burned when selling a used car. He bought a 2018 Audi A4L that looked to be in good condition and was reasonably priced.
Ye Mingxuan: And then? Is there a problem with the car?

Zhang Wei: It's a serious issue. He didn't thoroughly check the maintenance records of the transmission. The car's transmission had undergone major repairs, but the records were deliberately concealed. Now, after driving for just a month, the customer encountered a malfunction and came to seek redress, causing quite a stir. The company internally issued a reprimand against him and imposed a fine. He'll likely lose his entire bonus this month. Sigh, the used car market is full of pitfalls; a single oversight can lead to disaster.
Sun Jing: Mingxuan, I heard from Xiaofeng that you've been working on smart home devices lately? How's it going for your parents?

Ye Mingxuan: Yes, Sister Jing, it's basically all set. The smart door lock and lighting are all taken care of. Recently, I've been thinking about adding a smart speaker to make it easier for Mom and Dad to control things by voice.
Sun Jing: Have you decided on a target yet? Xiaomi AI Speaker, Tmall Genie, or HomePod?
Ye Mingxuan: I've basically decided on Xiao Ai. The sound quality is good enough for my parents, and they aren't particularly sensitive to whether the AI assistant responds quickly or slowly.

Ye Mingxuan: The most crucial point is that the smart bulbs and sockets I previously installed for them are all from the Xiaomi ecosystem. Choosing Xiao Ai means no hassle—with just one command, you can control the lights, check the weather, and it’s all effortless. Compatibility is what I value most; otherwise, these devices would just be decorative.
Ye Mingxuan: While waiting for my coffee at the cafe, I thought about designing the balcony flower stand to be modular, making it easier to adjust and expand. What do you think?
Liu Yang: Mingxuan, I've got something interesting to tell you!
Ye Mingxuan: What's up? You seem so excited.
Liu Yang: Last Saturday, I attended an embedded technology salon, which was held in the Shenzhen Nanshan Science and Technology Park.
Liu Yang: There was a prize draw at the end of the salon, and guess what? I actually won the first prize!
Ye Mingxuan: Sure! What did you win?
Liu Yang: A brand-new Creality K1 Max 3D printer! I was just wondering how to get started with it. Since you have experience, could you teach me how to use it sometime?
Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, have you seen the newly released "Alien: Romulus" yet? I heard the special effects are mind-blowing.
Ye Mingxuan: Yes, I watched it. I went with my dad last Saturday to see the IMAX version.
Zhou Tao: How do you feel? Is it worth watching?

Ye Mingxuan: The special effects and atmosphere are impeccable; Old Lei's craftsmanship is still evident. However, the plot progression is a bit slow, and the middle section feels somewhat dull. I prefer sci-fi films with a tight pace and rigorous logic.
Zhou Tao: Haha, indeed an engineer's perspective, prioritizing logic and efficiency. What about "Dune: Part Two"?
Ye Mingxuan: I watched Dune: Part Two last year. It has a stronger epic feel, but it's too grand and not the same genre as Alien.
Sun Jing: Mingxuan, how have you been lately? Is it cold in Tianjin? The wind in Beijing is frighteningly strong.
Ye Mingxuan: Not bad, the heating at home is good. Are you still as busy with work?
Sun Jing: Don't even mention it. The atmosphere in our team has been a bit down lately. A colleague's Southeast Asian smart city project got off to a rocky start.
Ye Mingxuan: Oh? Technical issues?

Sun Jing: It's not purely a technical issue. His preliminary research was insufficient; he didn't fully grasp the local religious taboos and residential building regulations. The first version of the conceptual design he submitted was directly rejected by the client, who said it was completely out of touch with reality. Now the entire project has to be postponed for a month for re-planning, and he's under immense pressure.
Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, are you free this weekend? The new DLC for *Black Myth: Wukong* is out. Want to team up?
Ye Mingxuan: This weekend probably won't work. The router at home keeps dropping the connection, which affects my parents' streaming and my remote meetings. I'm thinking about replacing it.
Zhou Tao: Haha, you're facing this issue too? I replaced mine last year, so I have some experience. What parameters are you mainly looking at?

Ye Mingxuan: Brand and price are secondary considerations. My home has many walls, so the most crucial factors are Wi-Fi 6 coverage and strong wall penetration capability. Otherwise, the signal in the study and master bedroom will definitely be poor. Even if the appearance is unattractive, it doesn't matter—stable signal is what truly matters.

Zhou Tao: Understood, a pragmatic approach. Then I recommend you take a look at a certain model from ASUS. I'm using one myself, and it handles three load-bearing walls without any pressure. I'll send you the link.

Ye Mingxuan: I listened to the Machinery Industry Information Institute's podcast during my morning commute, which discussed the progress in domestic production of high-end bearings. It provided valuable reference for my work.
Zhao Xiaofeng: Mingxuan, have you been in touch with Liu Yang recently? It seems he's dealing with some trouble over there.
Ye Mingxuan: We chatted while playing games last week, and he didn't mention anything. What's wrong?
Zhao Xiaofeng: His landlord suddenly decided to sell the house and asked him to move out within a month. As you know, the rental market in Shenzhen is tough, and he's now overwhelmed with stress.
Ye Mingxuan: So sudden? He had been renting that place for several years, hadn't he?

Zhao Xiaofeng: Yes, the contract is about to expire, so the landlord decided to sell it. He has looked at a few places these past few days and said the rents have all increased significantly compared to last year, so he's under quite a bit of pressure.

Zhang Wei: Good day, Mr. Ye. There are some structural opportunities in the market this quarter. We have recently launched several industry-specific ETFs focusing on semiconductors and new energy. They may exhibit higher volatility, but also offer greater potential returns. Would you be interested in learning more about them?
Ye Mingxuan: Good morning, Manager Zhang. Thank you for the recommendation. However, I still lean toward more stable options. I am not considering highly volatile, leveraged ETFs for the time being.
Zhang Wei: Understood, I see your preferences. What do you think about long-term sectors like consumption and pharmaceuticals, or using pure bond funds as a base allocation?

Ye Mingxuan: Please send me information on thematic funds focusing on consumption and pharmaceuticals. I have consistently allocated to pure bond funds and feel relatively assured by them. The primary consideration remains risk control as the top priority.
Sun Jing: Mingxuan, have you been busy lately? I had a video call with Liu Yang yesterday, and he told me a really funny story.
Ye Mingxuan: Not bad, just finished a project. Does Yangzi have any new jokes?
Sun Jing: Their company had a team-building event in Shenzhen last week. During the meal, everyone urged him to perform. Can you guess what he performed?
Ye Mingxuan: I really can't guess. It couldn't be playing video games, could it?

Sun Jing: Haha, he did an impromptu imitation of our university's Professor Chen who taught mechanical drawing! Pushing up his glasses, clasping his hands behind his back, and explaining force analysis in that cadenced tone—it's said he mimicked it exceptionally well, making all the colleagues present burst into laughter.
Ye Mingxuan: Oh my goodness, this imagery is so vivid. If Professor Chen finds out, I don't know whether he'll be pleased or exasperated.

Sun Jing: Indeed, Liu Yang said he regretted it right after the performance, feeling he was too "unsteady" in front of the department head and several senior executives. Thinking back on it now, he still finds it somewhat amusing and embarrassing.
Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, have you seen the recent film "Echoes of Deep Space"? The online reviews are polarized.
Ye Mingxuan: Not yet, I've been busy working on the 3D printing model of the flower stand recently. What did the evaluation say?
Zhou Tao: The special effects and visuals have been highly praised as groundbreaking. However, many have criticized the plot for being clichéd and the characters' motivations as unconvincing.

Ye Mingxuan: Special effects are a bonus for me, not a deciding factor. When I evaluate science fiction films, the most crucial criterion is whether the technological framework they establish is logically sound.
Zhou Tao: Such as?

Ye Mingxuan: For example, whether there is basic logic in the spacecraft's structure and propulsion principles, whether the design of the operation interface conforms to ergonomics, and even if it's just a tool in the background, whether its form and function are reasonable. Only the rigor of details can construct a believable future world. With only flashy visuals and touching stories, if the technological core is hollow, I feel it falls somewhat short.

Zhou Tao: Understood. Your engineer's professional habits are deeply ingrained. It seems the vaguely explained principle of the "hyperspace jump engine" criticized in "Echoes of Deep Space" definitely wouldn't pass your scrutiny.
Zhang Wei: Mingxuan, are you free this weekend? Let's go grab some skewers. I've had a lot on my mind lately and want to talk to someone.
Ye Mingxuan: Sure, the usual place? What's wrong, work not going well?
Zhang Wei: Indeed, cars haven't been selling well lately. By the way, do you remember our elementary school classmate Li Na? The one who works at Tencent in Shenzhen.
Ye Mingxuan: Remember, Nana, the one who does design. What happened to her?

Zhang Wei: She was also laid off, just last month. With the internet industry's winter, even big companies like Tencent can't withstand it. She's really worried; the pressure in Shenzhen is too much. But she's highly capable and should find another job soon. It doesn't directly concern us, but it's quite poignant to hear. We used to think big companies were so stable.
Sun Jing: Mingxuan, any good TV series recommendations lately? I'm running out of shows to watch.
Ye Mingxuan: Sister Jing, I haven't been watching many TV series lately; I've been watching more variety shows.
Sun Jing: Variety shows are fine too. Your taste has always been quite unique. What kind of shows do you like to watch?

Ye Mingxuan: I'm still the same as always, and I enjoy watching shows with a competitive element the most. For example, pure competition shows like "Street Dance of China," or reality shows with a bit of craftsmanship and engineering challenge, like "Dream Home." Watching others solve problems and complete projects is really exciting—more interesting than watching fictional dramas.
Sun Jing: Got it, your engineer's DNA is kicking in. Alright, I'll go look for similar documentaries to watch.
Ye Mingyuan: Mingxuan, how have you been lately? Has the weather in Tianjin warmed up?
Ye Mingxuan: Not bad, it's spring now. How about you, Brother Yuan? You don't sound quite right from your tone?

Ye Mingyuan: Ah, don't even mention it. Things have been a bit frustrating at work lately. I've been leading my team on a project for almost six months, and we had polished everything from the requirements to the prototype. But then, a notice came from above saying that due to strategic adjustments, the project was directly halted.
Ye Mingxuan: Huh? So suddenly? Then all the hard work your team has put in over the past six months would have been in vain?

Ye Mingyuan: Yes, it feels particularly disheartening, and everyone's morale is quite low. I've been adjusting my mindset these past few days, thinking about how to explain the situation to the team and offer some reassurance.
Zhou Tao: Mingxuan, any plans for the weekend? Would you like to go watch a movie? There seems to be a good sci-fi film out recently.

Ye Mingxuan: I plan to stay home and rest this weekend. Recently, I discovered a new variety show called "Extreme Brain Power King" that's quite interesting, so I'm going to catch up on the latest episodes.
Zhou Tao: "Ultimate Brain Power King"? Never heard of it. What's it about? Another singing and dancing show?

Ye Mingxuan: No, it's purely an intellectual competition. The participants are mostly programmers, engineers, mathematicians, and people with similar backgrounds. They compete by solving various complex logic puzzles, programming challenges, and mechanical structure problems. It's extremely mind-bending and incredibly satisfying to watch.
Zhou Tao: Sounds like something right up your alley as a STEM guy. Alright, go ahead and watch it then. Let's plan for next week.

Dad, after fixing the water tap this afternoon, I felt a bit of discomfort in my lower back, probably because I was bending over for too long. Next time I do this kind of work, I need to pay more attention to my posture or take more breaks in between.

I had a chat with Old Li today. He has a few silver coins from the Republic of China era in good condition, especially the Yuan Datou coins, but quality items don’t come cheap. How is the market on your end?

Zhao Jianguo: Mingxuan, your approach to data organization is excellent. Structuring the information will indeed facilitate research and communication. Regarding the Song Dynasty coins you mentioned last time, I have several professional catalogues on hand. I will send you the electronic versions for reference later.
Master Qian: Mingxuan, I really enjoyed our conversation yesterday. I've sent the feedback on your box to your email. Please take a look when you have a moment. The work is indeed excellent.
Wang Jian: Mingxuan, should we cancel or adjust tomorrow's regular training session? I noticed you've been walking a bit off these past couple of days.

message_content: Lao Zhao, I have to work overtime tonight to review the drawings, so the scheduled basketball game is canceled. Let's reschedule for another day.

(To Gao Zhiyuan) I've been busy with household matters and project reviews from morning till night today, completely exhausted. The exercise I originally planned will have to be postponed for now. I need to push through these next few days to meet the deadline.
I have to work through the night to complete the review, so all activities are canceled and exercise will have to wait for another day. I'm simply too exhausted.

Mingxuan, I recall you mentioned last time that your advisor Professor Chen also enjoys collecting modern antique coins? I have a client in the cultural and creative industry who has just released a batch of limited-edition replicas. I think there's one particular item that would be especially suitable as a gift. Would you be interested in learning more about it?

The replica mentioned last time is the centennial commemorative edition of the "Guangxu Yuanbao (Beiyang Mint, Kuping One Tael)." Both the craftsmanship and packaging are quite exquisite, making it a suitable small gift for your supervisor. I've sent you the picture.
Mingxuan, I'm going back to Tianjin during the May Day holiday! Let's get together then—it's been a while since I've had authentic Goubuli. I should be free on the second day after returning home.
My flight is on the evening of April 30th, and I expect to arrive very late. I'll contact you the next day to see which shops are open.

Xiao Xuan, if you come to make that toolbox next week, I've saved a fine piece of white oak for you. It has a hard texture and beautiful grain, making it more suitable than the pine wood you used last time.

Last time you asked about materials for making small ornaments. In addition to white oak, you could also consider black walnut and cherry wood. A batch of North American cherry wood has recently arrived, featuring a warm color and excellent texture. Feel free to come and take a look when you have time.
Son, I bought a particularly good piece of pork belly today. Tomorrow I'll make your favorite braised pork. Remember to come home early for dinner.
Mingxuan, the market has fresh sea bass. I'll make steamed sea bass for you to change things up. You must be tired of the braised pork belly from last time, right?

Mingxuan, recently our project team has been working with a major client in Shenzhen, primarily focusing on the design of structural components for communication equipment. The requirements of 'that company' are exceptionally stringent, with a particularly extensive process.

The one I complained to you about having too many processes last time was Huawei. They recently have a new base station project with absolutely insane precision requirements, but being able to participate is still a great learning opportunity.
Son, do you have any special gift you want on "that day" this year? Your mom said she wants to celebrate it properly for you.

On your birthday, August 16th, I've discussed with your mother, and we've decided to take the whole family out for a nice meal. You can choose the place—it'll be our way of celebrating you growing another year older.

Brother Xuan, housing prices in Shenzhen have finally started to ease a bit. My family and I looked at a development called China Resources Land's Runfu near the Technology Park in Nanshan District. The layout and supporting facilities are quite good, so we're planning to make a purchase.

Nana, congratulations! The location of that new development near the Nanshan Technology Park is indeed excellent, with mature supporting facilities. Which residential community did you ultimately decide on?
It's about what I mentioned to you last time, the third phase of Runfu. I gritted my teeth and bought a three-bedroom apartment. Finally, I don't have to rent anymore!

Mingxuan, I've prepared small gifts for both you and Lei for the Spring Festival gathering. I've set aside a Beiyang Year 34 coin for you, and for Lei, I've prepared a signed edition, as he mentioned being particularly curious about it during our last video call.
You're such a great friend! The signed edition is really hard to find. Is it from three years ago?
Yes, three years of signatures, the condition is quite good. See you during the New Year!
Leizi, have you received the silver coin with the signature edition that Haozi sent you for the Spring Festival? He specifically picked it out for you.

Got it! So you mentioned last time that he really enjoys collecting modern machine-struck coins, right? That "Yuan Datou" three-year signed edition is so cool, with clear edge reeding. I even looked up some information—those with the L.GIORGI signature are indeed rare. Please thank Haozi for me!

Mingxuan, I spoke with Xiaofeng today, and he mentioned that you taught him a little trick last time to resolve software lagging issues. It worked particularly well, and his large assembly now runs much more smoothly.

Hi, you're welcome. He's also in the automotive parts industry and uses SolidWorks frequently, so the optimization settings for large assemblies are the same. Which specific technique did he mention works? Is it turning off real-time rendering or adjusting the high-performance options?
His exact words were, "The method Mingxuan taught for turning off RealView graphics display" — it stopped lagging immediately, and he praised your professionalism.
Mr. Zhou, last time you mentioned your friend who is exceptionally skilled at programming. He recently got very excited about some major news. Which company was it? Is it in AI or hardware?

Haha, it's Mingxuan, that programming buddy from Shenzhen named Xu Ming. He was incredibly excited yesterday because Google released a groundbreaking new framework, which those in backend development consider revolutionary.
Aming, I saw your WeChat Moments are flooded with shares. Did Google I/O Conference announce something groundbreaking? Is it about AI development frameworks?

Yes! Google has released the new generation of TensorFlow Lite Micro, which significantly optimizes AI deployment on edge devices. Our team is currently evaluating it, as this may change the development patterns of many products!
Master Qian, I found a piece of old elm wood at the antique market over the weekend. Its grain is particularly beautiful, and I plan to use it to make a dovetail jewelry box.

Excellent! Old elm wood has stable properties, making it suitable for fine mortise and tenon joints. Selecting the right material is half the battle. Pay attention to the moisture content during the process.

Master, I've finished that jewelry box. The texture of the old elm wood is truly excellent, and the color becomes quite warm after polishing. I'll send you a few photos of the finished product so you can see the details of the mortise and tenon joints.

I've seen the picture. The dovetail joints fit tightly, and the edges are neatly finished. This piece of aged wood was well chosen—the grain pattern is beautifully displayed. Your craftsmanship has improved!

Mingxuan, are you available next Thursday evening? The first phase of the Haihe Project has been successfully delivered, and Manager Wang suggested that our team could have a simple dinner to celebrate.
Alright, Senior Engineer, I have no problem. Do you need me to make a reservation in advance?

Mr. Ye, the preliminary draft of the wedding financial planning proposal for your cousin, Mr. Ye Mingyuan, has been sent to your email. He has chosen to hold the ceremony in Shenzhen, which involves fund transfers between locations and the management of monetary gifts. We are currently refining these details. Would you be available for a phone call around next Thursday?

Master Qian, regarding the workbench I mentioned to you last time that I want to build myself, I have sent the design plan and dimension drawings to your email. How do you suggest we select the materials? My main priority is stability and durability, and the budget is not a major concern.

Xiao Xuan, I've reviewed the drawings, and the structure is fine. I suggest using the material from that workbench—it has moderate hardness, beautiful wood grain, and good insect resistance, though the price is slightly higher. If you think it's okay, I'll go ahead and order the material.

Recently, I saw several pieces of old camphor wood boards at the antique market, and their grain patterns were absolutely stunning. Unfortunately, the prices were too high. If used for furniture, the texture would undoubtedly be top-notch.

Teacher Zhao is absolutely right! My newly made workbench uses old camphor wood, sourced by Master Qian. The aroma and sheen after polishing are truly incomparable. It just gave my wallet a bit of a sting.
Yoko, how have you been lately? Want to team up for some gaming tonight?

Not tonight, I have to work overtime to finish a task. I've been pushing myself to the limit lately for that skin set, grinding and spending money like crazy. All my pocket money for this month is gone.

Haha, finally! I've collected the entire Jade Sword Legend skin series! The effects are absolutely stunning—this money was well spent! Mingxuan, have you bought that Jade Sword skin in the game? It feels great to use.
Congratulations, you're really persistent. I haven't bought it yet—I've been delving into a data analysis library for Python recently and have been playing fewer games.

Senior Engineer, the synchronization accuracy of the servo system at the client's factory has suddenly experienced severe deviation. The local technical support is unable to resolve the issue, so I need to bring debugging tools and spare parts and go there immediately.

Approved. Please ensure safety and bring the complete set of diagnostic logs. As this is your first business trip to such a distant location, feel free to contact us anytime if you encounter any difficulties.

Have you seen the news? Rongzhi Technology, the industrial robotics company in Chengdu, recently secured funding and is gaining strong momentum. In their newly released recruitment notice, they are offering a high salary to hire motion control algorithm engineers, requiring familiarity with multi-axis servo synchronization and vibration suppression. Isn't that exactly the challenging field you were tackling at the beginning of the year?
Noted. The offer is indeed attractive, but I still prefer the current company's focus on mechanical hardware and system integration. Let the software engineers handle the headache of algorithms.
Coach Wang, I'm in good form today. I think I'm almost able to achieve the challenge you mentioned last week.
Sure! Keep it up, engage your core, and pay attention to the rhythm. If you can complete it by this Wednesday, you'll be one of the fastest progressing trainees I've coached this year!

Mom, I have something interesting to tell you. My fitness trainer has made me a role model just because I did 60 standard push-ups in one go last month. He even used this example to motivate new trainees today.
Oh, my son is really amazing! But be careful not to get hurt. It was on September 24th, right? When your dad came back, he kept saying how exhausted you looked but also how incredibly happy you were.

Son, we're having a family dinner at home for the Mid-Autumn Festival, and your aunt's family will also be joining us. Your dad is in charge of preparing the fish and meat dishes, while I'll handle a few stir-fried dishes and soup. Since you're skilled in cooking, could you also bring a few of your signature specialties?
No problem, Mom. Leave it to me, I'll make sure everyone is satisfied with the meal. I'll prepare everything a day in advance.

Xiaofeng, happy Mid-Autumn Festival! The family gathering just ended today—tired but happy. The Goubuli steamed buns, spicy stir-fry hot pot, and fruit salad I made were the most popular and were finished in no time. Indeed, food lovers have discerning tastes.
Happy Mid-Autumn Festival! Impressive, Chef Ye, you've been hiding your skills. It sounds mouthwatering—you must show off your cooking at the next gathering.

Mr. Ye, urgent help needed! I have a business trip to Guangzhou early tomorrow morning and will be away for two weeks. There's no one to take care of the succulents on my balcony. Since you are the most attentive, could you please look after them for me? I've left the key with the property management.
Alright, no problem. Are there any specific considerations for watering? I'm worried I might damage it while taking care of it.

I'm back! Thank you so much for taking care of things! The succulent you helped water last time is in even better condition than when I was home. Did you follow the instructions on the label I left exactly?
Haha, yes. Your note saying "Water sparingly along the pot edge every Tuesday and Friday" is so prominently placed that it's hard to miss. But it really works—they all look quite healthy.

Mingxuan, while sorting through items in the old house today, I found an old silver coin in the corner of a drawer in a cabinet in the living room. It bears the inscription "Guangxu Yuanbao." I’m not sure if it’s the kind you collect?
Mom, that's great! The Guangxu Yuanbao coin is exactly within my collection scope. Please don't move it for now; I'll come back to take a look this weekend. Which drawer in which cabinet is it in?
It's that old five-drawer dresser left by your grandfather, over by the window in the living room. The old house hasn't been lived in for a long time, so there's quite a bit of dust.
Weizi, I'm going to the old house in Xiqing this weekend. My mom found some old items there. It's at 128 Zhongbei Avenue, you know that place, right? We used to play there often when we were kids.
Yes, I know, your old family home. Why are you suddenly thinking about the past? Do you need any help?

Mr. Zhou, I recall you mentioned wanting to learn some Python data analysis last time. The online course platform I enrolled in last year is quite good, with plenty of hands-on projects. It's called Data... something—I'll look it up and send it to you in a moment.
Great! Thank you, Engineer Ye! I was just worried about finding suitable entry-level resources. I'll be waiting for your message.

Aming, do you remember the DataCamp platform we used to take classes together? My colleague also wants to learn, and I noticed the courses have been updated quite a bit. Is it still the case that registering with that invitation link offers a discount?
Yes, DataCamp. I'll send you the link; there's a discount for new users in the first year. Their 'Python for Data Science' track is particularly beginner-friendly.

Son, I heard from some old colleagues at the factory that there are going to be major changes in our old factory area (the First Machine Tool Plant site). It seems the city has plans for it. An official announcement should be made in a couple of days.

Weizi, have you seen the news? The transformation of the Xiqing Old Industrial Zone is underway. The original site of the First Machine Tool Plant will be developed into a Digital Intelligent Manufacturing Industrial Park. It was just announced today.
Just saw this! Quite a stir it's causing. So it seems the old factory area from your father's generation's memory is really going to change.
Dabin, if we plan to travel the Northwest Loop this year, around September or October, which time period would offer the best experience?

The early to mid-October period offers absolutely stunning autumn scenery. However, it is crucial to avoid the crowds during the National Day holiday, as the roads and scenic spots can be overwhelming in the first five days. Late September or mid to late October are both suitable times to travel.
Mom, I might go out with friends for a few days during the National Day holiday and won't be home. It depends on the arrangements.
Driving again? This year's National Day holiday is from October 1st to 7th. Drive safely and book your accommodation early.
Master Qian, I'd like to try making a small tea tray and would prefer to use Huanghuali wood. Do you know where I can purchase reliable materials in Tianjin or the surrounding areas?

The market for Huanghuali wood can be quite complex. Good quality materials are scarce in Tianjin locally. I know of an old market in Hebei province that specializes in wood furniture, and they have some older stock available. I'll send you the address. Let me know before you go, and I can make an introduction for you.
Dad, isn't my mom's hometown Cangzhou? Is there a fairly large traditional timber market there? My woodworking master recommended it.
Yes, there's an old market in Cangzhou that your grandfather's generation knew about. Are you going to buy wood? Have your mother ask her relatives on her side.
Mr. Li, how has your fitness progress been lately? My coach always recommends that I take some protein powder, saying it improves muscle-building efficiency.
I'm drinking it. My coach also recommended a British brand, saying it offers good value for money. Its English name starts with M, and I'll send you the link later.
Brother Yuan, do you take protein powder for your workouts? My colleague's coach recommended a brand called Myprotein. Are you familiar with it?
Myprotein, a very common brand, can sometimes be quite cost-effective with direct overseas shipping. Have you started training seriously?
